[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The term has slightly different meanings in different branches of linguistics and computer science.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Traditional sentence parsing is often performed as a method of understanding the exact meaning of a sentence or word, sometimes with the aid of devices such as sentence diagrams.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] It usually emphasizes the importance of grammatical divisions such as subject and predicate.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Within computational linguistics the term is used to refer to the formal analysis by a computer of a sentence or other string of words into its constituents, resulting in a parse tree showing their syntactic relation to each other, which may also contain semantic information.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Some parsing algorithms generate a *parse forest* or list of parse trees from a string that is syntactically ambiguous.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The term is also used in psycholinguistics when describing language comprehension.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Within computer science, the term is used in the analysis of computer languages, referring to the syntactic analysis of the input code into its component parts in order to facilitate the writing of compilers and interpreters.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The term may also be used to describe a split or separation.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In data analysis, the term is often used to refer to a process extracting desired information from data, e.g., creating a time series signal from a XML document.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The traditional grammatical exercise of parsing, sometimes known as *clause analysis*, involves breaking down a text into its component parts of speech with an explanation of the form, function, and syntactic relationship of each part.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This is determined in large part from study of the language's conjugations and declensions, which can be quite intricate for heavily inflected languages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] To parse a phrase such as "man bites dog" involves noting that the singular noun "man" is the subject of the sentence, the verb "bites" is the third person singular of the present tense of the verb "to bite", and the singular noun "dog" is the object of the sentence.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Techniques such as sentence diagrams are sometimes used to indicate relation between elements in the sentence.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsing was formerly central to the teaching of grammar throughout the English-speaking world, and widely regarded as basic to the use and understanding of written language.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In some machine translation and natural language processing systems, written texts in human languages are parsed by computer programs.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Human sentences are not easily parsed by programs, as there is substantial ambiguity in the structure of human language, whose usage is to convey meaning (or semantics) amongst a potentially unlimited range of possibilities, but only some of which are germane to the particular case.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] So an utterance "Man bites dog" versus "Dog bites man" is definite on one detail but in another language might appear as "Man dog bites" with a reliance on the larger context to distinguish between those two possibilities, if indeed that difference was of concern.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] It is difficult to prepare formal rules to describe informal behaviour even though it is clear that some rules are being followed.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In order to parse natural language data, researchers must first agree on the grammar to be used.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The choice of syntax is affected by both linguistic and computational concerns; for instance some parsing systems use lexical functional grammar, but in general, parsing for grammars of this type is known to be NP-complete.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Head-driven phrase structure grammar is another linguistic formalism which has been popular in the parsing community, but other research efforts have focused on less complex formalisms such as the one used in the Penn Treebank.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shallow parsing aims to find only the boundaries of major constituents such as noun phrases.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Another popular strategy for avoiding linguistic controversy is dependency grammar parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Most modern parsers are at least partly statistical; that is, they rely on a corpus of training data which has already been annotated (parsed by hand).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This approach allows the system to gather information about the frequency with which various constructions occur in specific contexts.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] *(See machine learning.)* Approaches which have been used include straightforward PCFGs (probabilistic context-free grammars), maximum entropy, and neural nets.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Most of the more successful systems use *lexical* statistics (that is, they consider the identities of the words involved, as well as their part of speech).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] However such systems are vulnerable to overfitting and require some kind of smoothing to be effective.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsing algorithms for natural language cannot rely on the grammar having 'nice' properties as with manually designed grammars for programming languages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] As mentioned earlier some grammar formalisms are very difficult to parse computationally; in general, even if the desired structure is not context-free, some kind of context-free approximation to the grammar is used to perform a first pass.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Algorithms which use context-free grammars often rely on some variant of the CYK algorithm, usually with some heuristic to prune away unlikely analyses to save time.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] *(See chart parsing.)* However some systems trade speed for accuracy using, e.g., linear-time versions of the shift-reduce algorithm.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] A somewhat recent development has been parse reranking in which the parser proposes some large number of analyses, and a more complex system selects the best option.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In natural language understanding applications, semantic parsers convert the text into a representation of its meaning.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In psycholinguistics, parsing involves not just the assignment of words to categories (formation of ontological insights), but the evaluation of the meaning of a sentence according to the rules of syntax drawn by inferences made from each word in the sentence (known as connotation).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This normally occurs as words are being heard or read.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Neurolinguistics generally understands parsing to be a function of working memory, meaning that parsing is used to keep several parts of one sentence at play in the mind at one time, all readily accessible to be analyzed as needed.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Because the human working memory has limitations, so does the function of sentence parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This is evidenced by several different types of syntactically complex sentences that demonstrate potential issues for mental parsing of sentences.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The first, and perhaps most well-known, type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is the garden-path sentence.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] These sentences are designed so that the most common interpretation of the sentence appears grammatically faulty, but upon further inspection, these sentences are grammatically sound.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Garden-path sentences are difficult to parse because they contain a phrase or a word with more than one meaning, often their most typical meaning being a different part of speech.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] For example, in the sentence, "the horse raced past the barn fell", raced is initially interpreted as a past tense verb, but in this sentence, it functions as part of an adjective phrase.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Since parsing is used to identify parts of speech, these sentences challenge the parsing ability of the reader.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Another type of sentence that is difficult to parse is an attachment ambiguity, which includes a phrase that could potentially modify different parts of a sentence, and therefore presents a challenge in identifying syntactic relationship (i.e.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] A third type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is center embedding, in which phrases are placed in the center of other similarly formed phrases (i.e.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] "The rat the cat the man hit chased ran into the trap".) Sentences with 2 or in the most extreme cases 3 center embeddings are challenging for mental parsing, again because of ambiguity of syntactic relationship.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Within neurolinguistics there are multiple theories that aim to describe how parsing takes place in the brain.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The opposing, more contemporary model theorizes that within the mind, the processing of a sentence is not modular, or happening in strict sequence.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Rather, it poses that several different syntactic possibilities can be considered at the same time, because lexical access, syntactic processing, and determination of meaning occur in parallel in the brain.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In this way these processes are integrated.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Although there is still much to learn about the neurology of parsing, studies have shown evidence that several areas of the brain might play a role in parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] These include the left anterior temporal pole, the left inferior frontal gyrus, the left superior temporal gyrus, the left superior frontal gyrus, the right posterior cingulate cortex, and the left angular gyrus.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Although it has not been absolutely proven, it has been suggested that these different structures might favor either phrase-structure parsing or dependency-structure parsing, meaning different types of parsing could be processed in different ways which have yet to be understood.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Discourse analysis examines ways to analyze language use and semiotic events.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Persuasive language may be called rhetoric.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] A **parser** is a software component that takes input data (typically text) and builds a data structure – often some kind of parse tree, abstract syntax tree or other hierarchical structure, giving a structural representation of the input while checking for correct syntax.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The parsing may be preceded or followed by other steps, or these may be combined into a single step.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The parser is often preceded by a separate lexical analyser, which creates tokens from the sequence of input characters; alternatively, these can be combined in scannerless parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsers may be programmed by hand or may be automatically or semi-automatically generated by a parser generator.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsing is complementary to templating, which produces formatted *output.* These may be applied to different domains, but often appear together, such as the scanf/printf pair, or the input (front end parsing) and output (back end code generation) stages of a compiler.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The input to a parser is typically text in some computer language, but may also be text in a natural language or less structured textual data, in which case generally only certain parts of the text are extracted, rather than a parse tree being constructed.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsers range from very simple functions such as scanf, to complex programs such as the frontend of a C++ compiler or the HTML parser of a web browser.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] An important class of simple parsing is done using regular expressions, in which a group of regular expressions defines a regular language and a regular expression engine automatically generating a parser for that language, allowing pattern matching and extraction of text.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In other contexts regular expressions are instead used prior to parsing, as the lexing step whose output is then used by the parser.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In the case of data languages, a parser is often found as the file reading facility of a program, such as reading in HTML or XML text; these examples are markup languages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In the case of programming languages, a parser is a component of a compiler or interpreter, which parses the source code of a computer programming language to create some form of internal representation; the parser is a key step in the compiler frontend.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Programming languages tend to be specified in terms of a deterministic context-free grammar because fast and efficient parsers can be written for them.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] For compilers, the parsing itself can be done in one pass or multiple passes – see one-pass compiler and multi-pass compiler.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The implied disadvantages of a one-pass compiler can largely be overcome by adding fix-ups, where provision is made for code relocation during the forward pass, and the fix-ups are applied backwards when the current program segment has been recognized as having been completed.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] An example where such a fix-up mechanism would be useful would be a forward GOTO statement, where the target of the GOTO is unknown until the program segment is completed.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In this case, the application of the fix-up would be delayed until the target of the GOTO was recognized.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Conversely, a backward GOTO does not require a fix-up, as the location will already be known.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Context-free grammars are limited in the extent to which they can express all of the requirements of a language.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Informally, the reason is that the memory of such a language is limited.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The grammar cannot remember the presence of a construct over an arbitrarily long input; this is necessary for a language in which, for example, a name must be declared before it may be referenced.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] More powerful grammars that can express this constraint, however, cannot be parsed efficiently.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Thus, it is a common strategy to create a relaxed parser for a context-free grammar which accepts a superset of the desired language constructs (that is, it accepts some invalid constructs); later, the unwanted constructs can be filtered out at the semantic analysis (contextual analysis) step.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The following example demonstrates the common case of parsing a computer language with two levels of grammar: lexical and syntactic.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The first stage is the token generation, or lexical analysis, by which the input character stream is split into meaningful symbols defined by a grammar of regular expressions.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] For example, a calculator program would look at an input such as "`12 * (3 + 4)^2`" and split it into the tokens `12`, `*`, `(`, `3`, `+`, `4`, `)`, `^`, `2`, each of which is a meaningful symbol in the context of an arithmetic expression.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The lexer would contain rules to tell it that the characters `*`, `+`, `^`, `(` and `)` mark the start of a new token, so meaningless tokens like "`12*`" or "`(3`" will not be generated.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The next stage is parsing or syntactic analysis, which is checking that the tokens form an allowable expression.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This is usually done with reference to a context-free grammar which recursively defines components that can make up an expression and the order in which they must appear.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] However, not all rules defining programming languages can be expressed by context-free grammars alone, for example type validity and proper declaration of identifiers.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] These rules can be formally expressed with attribute grammars.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The final phase is semantic parsing or analysis, which is working out the implications of the expression just validated and taking the appropriate action.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] In the case of a calculator or interpreter, the action is to evaluate the expression or program; a compiler, on the other hand, would generate some kind of code.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Attribute grammars can also be used to define these actions.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The *task* of the parser is essentially to determine if and how the input can be derived from the start symbol of the grammar.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] by expanding all alternative right-hand-sides of grammar rules.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This is known as the primordial soup approach.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Very similar to sentence diagramming, primordial soup breaks down the constituencies of sentences.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] A parser can start with the input and attempt to rewrite it to the start symbol.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Intuitively, the parser attempts to locate the most basic elements, then the elements containing these, and so on.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] LL parsers and recursive-descent parser are examples of top-down parsers that cannot accommodate left recursive production rules.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Their algorithm is able to produce both left-most and right-most derivations of an input with regard to a given context-free grammar.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] An important distinction with regard to parsers is whether a parser generates a *leftmost derivation* or a *rightmost derivation* (see context-free grammar).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] LL parsers will generate a leftmost derivation and LR parsers will generate a rightmost derivation (although usually in reverse).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Some *graphical parsing* algorithms have been designed for visual programming languages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Parsers for visual languages are sometimes based on graph grammars.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Adaptive parsing algorithms have been used to construct "self-extending" natural language user interfaces.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] A simple parser implementation reads the entire input file, performs an intermediate computation or translation, and then writes the entire output file, such as in-memory multi-pass compilers.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Lookahead establishes the maximum incoming tokens that a parser can use to decide which rule it should use.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Lookahead is especially relevant to LL, LR, and LALR parsers, where it is often explicitly indicated by affixing the lookahead to the algorithm name in parentheses, such as LALR(1).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Most programming languages, the primary target of parsers, are carefully defined in such a way that a parser with limited lookahead, typically one, can parse them, because parsers with limited lookahead are often more efficient.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] One important change to this trend came in 1990 when Terence Parr created ANTLR for his Ph.D. thesis, a parser generator for efficient LL(*k*) parsers, where *k* is any fixed value.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] LR parsers typically have only a few actions after seeing each token.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] They are shift (add this token to the stack for later reduction), reduce (pop tokens from the stack and form a syntactic construct), end, error (no known rule applies) or conflict (does not know whether to shift or reduce).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Most programming languages (except for a few such as APL and Smalltalk) and algebraic formulas give higher precedence to multiplication than addition, in which case the correct interpretation of the example above is 1 + (2 * 3).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Note that Rule4 above is a semantic rule.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] It is possible to rewrite the grammar to incorporate this into the syntax.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] However, not all such rules can be translated into syntax.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduces "1" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift "+" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule1).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift "2" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack element "2" to Expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, +, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule1.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift "*" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule2).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift "3" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack element "3" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, *, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule2.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The parse tree and resulting code from it is not correct according to language semantics.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack item 1 to simple Expression on input + based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The lookahead is +, so we are on path to E +, so we can reduce the stack to E.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift + onto stack on input + in anticipation of rule1.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift 2 onto stack on input 2 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack item 2 to Expression on input * based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The lookahead * expects only E before it.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Now stack has E + E and still the input is *.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] It has two choices now, either to shift based on rule2 or reduction based on rule1.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Since * has higher precedence than + based on rule4, we shift * onto stack in anticipation of rule2.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Shift 3 onto stack on input 3 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack item 3 to Expression after seeing end of input based on rule3.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack items E * E to E based on rule2.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] Reduce stack items E + E to E based on rule1.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] The parse tree generated is correct and simply more efficient than non-lookahead parsers.
[src:cheerio-parsing/parsing] This is the strategy followed in LALR parsers.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Scraping a web page involves fetching it and then extracting data from it.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Fetching is the downloading of a page (which a browser does when a user views a page).
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Therefore, web crawling is a main component of web scraping, to fetch pages for later processing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Having fetched, extraction can take place.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The content of a page may be parsed, searched and reformatted, and its data copied into a spreadsheet or loaded into a database.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Web scrapers typically take something out of a page, to make use of it for another purpose somewhere else.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] An example would be finding and copying names and telephone numbers, companies and their URLs, or e-mail addresses to a list (contact scraping).
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Another example is collecting competitors product prices for marketing purposes, which can involve gathering large-scale pricing datasets from e-commerce websites and analysing them using data science techniques such as trend analysis, predictive modelling, and competitive benchmarking.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Web pages are built using text-based markup languages (HTML and XHTML), and frequently contain a wealth of data in text form.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] However, most web pages are designed for human end-users and not for ease of automated use.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] As a result, specialized tools and software have been developed to facilitate the scraping of web pages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Web scraping applications include market research, price comparison, content monitoring and artificial intelligence.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Businesses rely on web scraping services to efficiently gather and utilize this data.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Newer forms of web scraping involve monitoring data feeds from web servers.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] For example, JSON is commonly used as a transport mechanism between the client and the web server.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] There are methods that some websites use to prevent web scraping, such as detecting and disallowing bots from crawling (viewing) their pages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In response, web scraping systems use techniques involving DOM parsing, computer vision and natural language processing to simulate human-like browsing to enable gathering web page content for offline parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] After the birth of the World Wide Web in 1989, the first web robot, World Wide Web Wanderer, was created in June 1993, which was intended only to measure the size of the web.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In December 1993, the first crawler-based web search engine, JumpStation, was launched.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] As there were fewer websites available on the web, search engines at that time used to rely on human administrators to collect and format links.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In comparison, Jump Station was the first WWW search engine to rely on a web robot.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In 2000, the first Web API and API crawler were created.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In 2000, Salesforce and eBay launched their own API, with which programmers could access and download some of the data available to the public.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Since then, many websites offer web APIs for people to access their public database.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Data extraction techniques range from manual collection to sophisticated automated systems.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Advanced methods analyze the underlying structure of web pages to transform unstructured content into a machine-readable format.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] These techniques utilize text processing or artificial intelligence, aligning with the technical goals of the Semantic Web.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The simplest form of web scraping is manual copying and pasting of data from a web page into a text file or spreadsheet.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This approach requires no technical tools and can be used when automated scraping is blocked by website restrictions or when human judgment is necessary to interpret complex content.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] However, manual scraping is highly inefficient for large datasets, as it is time-consuming, prone to human error, and mentally exhausting.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] For this reason, it is generally considered impractical compared to automated methods, except in cases where automation is not feasible.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] A simple approach to extract information from web pages is to use the UNIX grep command or regular expression-matching facilities of programming languages (for instance Perl or Python), in order to find text matching a specified pattern.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Static and dynamic web pages can be retrieved by posting HTTP requests to the remote web server using socket programming.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Many websites have large collections of pages generated dynamically from an underlying structured source, like a database.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Data of the same category are typically encoded into similar pages by a common script or template.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In data mining, a program that detects such templates in a particular information source, extracts its content, and translates it into a relational form, is called a wrapper.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Wrapper generation algorithms assume that input pages of a wrapper induction system conform to a common template and that they can be easily identified in terms of a URL common scheme.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Moreover, some semi-structured data query languages, such as XQuery and the HTQL, can be used to parse HTML pages and to retrieve and transform page content.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] By using a program such as Selenium or Playwright, developers can control a web browser such as Chrome or Firefox to load, navigate, and retrieve data from websites.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This method can be especially useful for scraping data from dynamic sites since a web browser will fully load each page.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Once an entire page is loaded, developers can access and parse the DOM using an expression language such as XPath.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] There are several companies that have developed vertical specific harvesting platforms.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] These platforms create and monitor a multitude of "bots" for specific verticals with no "man in the loop" (no direct human involvement), and no work related to a specific target site.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The preparation involves establishing the knowledge base for the entire vertical and then the platform creates the bots automatically.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The platform's robustness is measured by the quality of the information it retrieves (usually number of fields) and its scalability (how quick it can scale up to hundreds or thousands of sites).
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This scalability is mostly used to target the Long Tail of sites that common aggregators find complicated or too labor-intensive to harvest content from.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The pages being scraped may embrace metadata or semantic markups and annotations, which can be used to locate specific data snippets.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] If the annotations are embedded in the pages, as Microformat does, this technique can be viewed as a special case of DOM parsing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In another case, the annotations, organized into a semantic layer, are stored and managed separately from the web pages, so the scrapers can retrieve data schema and instructions from this layer before scraping the pages.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] There are efforts using machine learning and computer vision that attempt to identify and extract information from web pages by interpreting pages visually as a human being might.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The legality of web scraping varies across the world.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In general, web scraping may be against the terms of service of some websites, but the enforceability of these terms is unclear.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In the United States, website owners can use three major legal claims to prevent undesired web scraping: (1) copyright infringement (compilation), (2) violation of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act ("CFAA"), and (3) trespass to chattel.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] However, the effectiveness of these claims relies upon meeting various criteria, and the case law is still evolving.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] For example, with regard to copyright, while outright duplication of original expression will in many cases be illegal, in the United States the courts ruled in *Feist Publications v.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Rural Telephone Service* that duplication of facts is allowable.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] U.S. courts have acknowledged that users of "scrapers" or "robots" may be held liable for committing trespass to chattels, which involves a computer system itself being considered personal property upon which the user of a scraper is trespassing.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Bidder's Edge*, resulted in an injunction ordering Bidder's Edge to stop accessing, collecting, and indexing auctions from the eBay web site.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This case involved automatic placing of bids, known as auction sniping.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Not all cases of web spidering brought before the courts have been considered trespass to chattels.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] One of the first major tests of screen scraping involved American Airlines (AA), and a firm called FareChase.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] AA successfully obtained an injunction from a Texas trial court, stopping FareChase from selling software that enables users to compare online fares if the software also searches AA's website.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The airline argued that FareChase's websearch software trespassed on AA's servers when it collected the publicly available data.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] FareChase filed an appeal in March 2003.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] By June, FareChase and AA agreed to settle and the appeal was dropped.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines has also challenged screen-scraping practices, and has involved both FareChase and another firm, Outtask, in a legal claim.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines charged that the screen-scraping is Illegal since it is an example of "Computer Fraud and Abuse" and has led to "Damage and Loss" and "Unauthorized Access" of Southwest's site.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] It also constitutes "Interference with Business Relations", "Trespass", and "Harmful Access by Computer".
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] They also claimed that screen-scraping constitutes what is legally known as "Misappropriation and Unjust Enrichment", as well as being a breach of the web site's user agreement.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Outtask denied all these claims, claiming that the prevailing law, in this case, should be US Copyright law and that under copyright, the pieces of information being scraped would not be subject to copyright protection.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Although the cases were never resolved in the Supreme Court of the United States, FareChase was eventually shuttered by parent company Yahoo!, and Outtask was purchased by travel expense company Concur.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In 2012, a startup called 3Taps scraped classified housing ads from Craigslist.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Craigslist sent 3Taps a cease-and-desist letter and blocked their IP addresses and later sued, in *Craigslist v.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The court held that the cease-and-desist letter and IP blocking was sufficient for Craigslist to properly claim that 3Taps had violated the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA).
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Although these are early scraping decisions, and the theories of liability are not uniform, it is difficult to ignore a pattern emerging that the courts are prepared to protect proprietary content on commercial sites from uses which are undesirable to the owners of such sites.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] While the law in this area becomes more settled, entities contemplating using scraping programs to access a public web site should also consider whether such action is authorized by reviewing the terms of use and other terms or notices posted on or made available through the site.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Eventbrite Inc.* (2010), the United States district court for the eastern district of Virginia, ruled that the terms of use should be brought to the users' attention in order for a browsewrap contract or license to be enforceable.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In a 2014 case, filed in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania, e-commerce site QVC objected to the Pinterest-like shopping aggregator Resultly's 'scraping of QVC's site for real-time pricing data.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] QVC alleges that Resultly "excessively crawled" QVC's retail site (allegedly sending 200-300 search requests to QVC's website per minute, sometimes to up to 36,000 requests per minute) which caused QVC's site to crash for two days, resulting in lost sales for QVC.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] QVC's complaint alleges that the defendant disguised its web crawler to mask its source IP address and thus prevented QVC from quickly repairing the problem.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This is a particularly interesting scraping case because QVC is seeking damages for the unavailability of their website, which QVC claims was caused by Resultly.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In the plaintiff's web site during the period of this trial, the terms of use link are displayed among all the links of the site, at the bottom of the page as most sites on the internet.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] This ruling contradicts the Irish ruling described below.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The court also rejected the plaintiff's argument that the browse-wrap restrictions were enforceable in view of Virginia's adoption of the Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act (UCITA)—a uniform law that many believed was in favor on common browse-wrap contracting practices.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Power Ventures, Inc.*, a district court ruled in 2012 that Power Ventures could not scrape Facebook pages on behalf of a Facebook user.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The case is on appeal, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation filed a brief in 2015 asking that it be overturned.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Holdings, Inc.*, a court in the US held Meltwater liable for scraping and republishing news information from the Associated Press, but a court in the United Kingdom held in favor of Meltwater.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The Ninth Circuit ruled in 2019 that web scraping did not violate the CFAA in *hiQ Labs v.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The case was appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which returned the case to the Ninth Circuit to reconsider the case in light of the 2021 Supreme Court decision in *Van Buren v.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] United States* which narrowed the applicability of the CFAA.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] On this review, the Ninth Circuit upheld their prior decision.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Internet Archive collects and distributes a significant number of publicly available web pages without being considered to be in violation of copyright laws.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In February 2006, the Danish Maritime and Commercial Court (Copenhagen) ruled that systematic crawling, indexing, and deep linking by portal site ofir.dk of real estate site Home.dk does not conflict with Danish law or the database directive of the European Union.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Ethical data scraping supports offmarket sourcing in business but must comply with GDPR to avoid privacy violations in automated data collection.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In a February 2010 case complicated by matters of jurisdiction, Ireland's High Court delivered a verdict that illustrates the inchoate state of developing case law.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In the case of *Ryanair Ltd v Billigfluege.de GmbH*, Ireland's High Court ruled Ryanair's "click-wrap" agreement to be legally binding.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The decision is under appeal in Ireland's Supreme Court.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] On April 30, 2020, the French Data Protection Authority (CNIL) released new guidelines on web scraping.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The CNIL guidelines made it clear that publicly available data is still personal data and cannot be repurposed without the knowledge of the person to whom that data belongs.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] In Australia, the Spam Act 2003 outlaws some forms of web harvesting, although this only applies to email addresses.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] Besides a few cases dealing with IPR infringement, Indian courts have not expressly ruled on the legality of web scraping.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] However, since all common forms of electronic contracts are enforceable in India, violating the terms of use prohibiting data scraping will be a violation of the contract law.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] It will also violate the Information Technology Act, 2000, which penalizes unauthorized access to a computer resource or extracting data from a computer resource.
[src:cheerio-parsing/web-scraping] The administrator of a website can use various measures to stop or slow a bot.
